{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659530"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20868"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20868"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97380"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79995"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12325"},{"type":"tags","id":"12692"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97380"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECh\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome is a rare inherited disorder affecting multiple body systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological defect in Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deficiency of C2","Inherited defect in microbicidal activity","Inherited defect in leucocyte adhesion","Defects in Toll-like receptor (TLR) signalling","Inherited defect in phagolysosome function"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInherited defect in phagolysosome function\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary pathophysiological defect in Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome. This rare autosomal recessive disorder occurs due to a mutation in the LYST (lysosomal trafficking regulator) gene, which leads to abnormal fusion of lysosomes with phagosomes. The result is impaired intracellular digestion of phagocytosed microorganisms, contributing to recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInherited defects in leucocyte adhesion\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes Leucocyte Adhesion Deficiency (LAD), where neutrophils cannot adhere to endothelium and migrate to sites of infection due to defects in integrin molecules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefects in TLR signalling\u003C/strong\u003E - Toll-like receptor signalling defects would primarily affect pathogen recognition and innate immune activation, not phagolysosome function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInherited defects in microbicidal activity\u003C/strong\u003E - While this occurs secondarily in Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome, the primary defect is in phagolysosome formation and function, not in the microbicidal mechanisms themselves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of C2\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a complement deficiency that would affect the complement cascade, not phagolysosome function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic findings in Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome include partial albinism (due to defective melanosomes), recurrent pyogenic infections, and giant granules in leucocytes (due to abnormal lysosomal fusion). The syndrome typically progresses to an accelerated phase characterised by lymphohistiocytic infiltration of various organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome is a rare autosomal recessive disorder characterised by defects in lysosomal trafficking and phagolysosome fusion.","Patients with Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome present with partial albinism, recurrent infections, and giant granules in leucocytes.","The molecular defect in Ch\u00e9diak-Higashi syndrome involves mutations in the LYST gene, which regulates lysosomal trafficking."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 240-241."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20868"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:23:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:24:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97380"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12325"},"at